==Demographics==
The city is bilingual, both [[Finnish language|Finnish]] and [[Swedish language|Swedish]] being official languages.&lt;ref name=&quot;finlex&quot;&gt;[http://www.finlex.fi/fi/laki/alkup/2002/20021174 Government Decree on the Official Languages in Administrative Districts for 2003–2012 (in Finnish)];  [http://www.finlex.fi/sv/laki/alkup/2002/20021174] (the same in Swedish). Retrieved on 7 July 2012&lt;/ref&gt; A majority (78.7%) of the population are Finnish speakers while 2.4% speak Swedish as their first language. Vantaa's residents that speak a native language other than Finnish or Swedish stand at 18.9% of the population. Vantaa is home to a significant Estonian population.

In 2011, 199,236 of the municipality's 203,001 residents lived in officially recognized [[Urban areas in Finland|urban areas]] ({{lang-fi|taajama}}; {{lang-sv|tätort}}). The remaining population lives in the few rural sections of Vantaa, such as those in [[Sotunki]] and [[Seutula]].&lt;ref name=&quot;taajaväestö 2011&quot;&gt;{{cite web| url =http://193.166.171.75/Dialog/varval.asp?ma=140_vaerak_tau_300&amp;ti=Taajama-aste+alueittain+31.12.2011&amp;path=../Database/StatFin/vrm/vaerak/&amp;lang=3&amp;multilang=fi | title =Taajama-aste alueittain 31.12.2011 | publisher=Tilastokeskus | accessdate= 23 March 2015}}{{dead link|date=July 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In 2018, 56.1% of the population were members of the [[Evangelical Lutheran Church of Finland|Lutheran Church of Finland]].

